SIMPLE: syzygy
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Syzygy
<hw>Syz"y*gy</hw> <pr>(s⟦icr⟧z"⟦icr⟧*j⟦ycr⟧)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>;
<plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Syzygies</plw> <pr>(-j⟦icr⟧z)</pr>.</plu>
<ety>[L. <ets>syzygia</ets> a joining together, conjunction, Gr.
<grk>syzygi`a</grk>; <grk>sy`n</grk> with + <grk>zeygny`nai</grk> to
join, <grk>zygo`n</grk> yoke: cf. F. <ets>syzygie</ets>. See
<er>Yoke</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Astron.)</fld>
<def>The point of an orbit, as of the moon or a planet, at which it is
in conjunction or opposition; -- commonly used in the plural.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Gr. & L. Pros.)</fld> <def>The coupling together of
different feet; <as>as, in Greek verse, an iambic
<ex>syzygy</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Any one of the
segments of an arm of a crinoid composed of two joints so closely united
that the line of union is obliterated on the outer, though visible on
the inner, side.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The immovable union of two
joints of a crinoidal arm.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The intimately united and apparently fused condition
of certain low organisms during conjugation.</def></p>

<p><cs><col><b>Line of syzygies</b></col> <fld>(Astron.)</fld>, <cd>the
straight line connecting the earth, the sun, and the moon or a planet,
when the latter is in conjunction or opposition; -- used chiefly of the
moon.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>


